      "content": "The solution is to realize that for this specific pathfinding problem, we only ever need the results from the previous row (or previous column, depending on iteration order). By using only two arrays—one for the current row and one for the previous row—we reduce the space complexity from $O(N \\cdot M)$ to $O(M)$, which is small enough for the memory limit. This technique is standard for space optimization in DP problems.\n\n```python\ndef solve_path_counting(N, M, grid):\n    if grid[0][0] == 1 or grid[N-1][M-1] == 1:\n        return 0\n\n    # dp_prev stores the path counts for the previous row (i-1)\n    # Initialize for the first row (i=0)\n    dp_prev = [0] * M\n    if grid[0][0] == 0:\n        dp_prev[0] = 1\n    for j in range(1, M):\n        if grid[0][j] == 0 and dp_prev[j-1] > 0:\n            dp_prev[j",
